just_use beginner.py

# label: INTRICATE
# role: Python-native PLANNER — beginner-level puzzle solver

The strategic brain for single-card stuck states. Given a
board with one or more "trouble" stacks (anything that
doesn't classify as set / pure_run / rb_run), search for a
shortest sequence of pulls + pushes that drives trouble
count to zero — within the cognitive budget of a beginner.

## The vocabulary

Trouble cards are the actors. They PULL helpers in or PUSH
themselves into existing legal structure. The DSL puts the
trouble stack first as the subject:

  6C:1 steal-pulls [5C] 6C:1 {-5C- 6C 7C}
  5C 6C:1 peel-pulls [4C] 5C 6C:1 {-4C- 4D 4S 4H}
  8C pushes-onto 8D 8S 8H [8C] {8D 8S 8H}

Helper card is in `[brackets]` where it landed; source
remnant in `{braces}` with the extracted card `-struck-`.
Deck-1 cards carry a `:1` suffix to disambiguate dups.

### Pull verbs (axis: source-side consequence)

| verb  | source remnant         | cost |
|-------|------------------------|------|
| peel  | still legal (length 4+ end-pull, or 4+ set) | 0 |
| pluck | both halves still legal (deep middle of long run) | 0 |
| yank  | one short partial (1 or 2) + one legal sub-run | +1 or +2 |
| steal | length-3 stack end-pull → 2-partial remnant | +2 |

`peel` vs `pluck` differ only on position (end vs middle) —
purely evocative, the algorithm collapses them.

### Push verbs (proposed, partially landed)

A loose orphan moves INTO an existing legal stack such that
the result remains legal. Currently implemented:
- **push-onto-set / push-onto-run END**: 3-set absorbs a
  4th of the missing suit; legal run grows by one card on
  an end. Tier 0b in the search; Δ trouble = −1, no
  source-side disruption.

Not yet implemented: SPLICE (insert into long-run middle),
SWAP (two-card type-converter trade).

## The search

Iterative deepening DFS (IDDFS) on number of compound moves.
At each depth limit, search tries:

- **Tier 0a** — free pull (existing loose absorbed by some
  trouble stack). No budget cost.
- **Tier 0b** — free push (existing loose lands on a legal
  stack, result legal). No budget cost.
- **Tier 1** — peel/pluck extract + pull. Budget −1.
- **Tier 2** — yank extract + pull. Budget −1.
- **Tier 3** — steal extract + pull. Budget −1.

Returns the first plan found (shortest by IDDFS). Safety
nets: max_compound depth cap (default 6), max_nodes
(200k), max_seconds (10s), per-depth visited cache.

## The taboo cycle-detector

When yank or steal fires, the extracted card carries a
deck-aware taboo set: it may not rejoin its former
stackmates. Without taboo, search cycles between steal-then-
restore-the-same-card. Deck-aware so 5C:1 can still join a
6C:0 even when 5C's taboo includes 6C of its original
stack.

## Coverage today

- 52/52 canonical 4/8 D2-card sweep solved.
- Push gate test (orphan onto existing 3-set) solves in 1
  step.
- Real-game stalls: ~65% rescue rate on hunts (measured
  pre-push; expected to rise).
- Plan length averages 1.5–2 compounds on canonical board;
  3 compounds typical on harder boards; 4+ rare.

Regression harness: `beginner_corpus.py` (canonical sweep +
gap cases). Pipe to file, `git diff` to compare runs.

## Pointers

- Companion architecture: `project_hints_are_client_side.md`
  (beginner.py is the Python-side hint logic post-trick-engine
  abandonment), `feedback_compound_move_budget.md`,
  `feedback_pull_vs_push.md`,
  `feedback_evocative_verbs_chunk.md`,
  `feedback_abundance_heuristic.md` (a hypothesis the
  planner doesn't yet model).
- Hunt drivers: `complex_hunt.py`, `deep_hunt.py`,
  `one_card_hunt.py`. They drive auto_player to a stall and
  call `beginner_plan` to see if the stall is a "Steve-level
  puzzle" (both engines stuck = sweet spot).
- Corpus: `beginner_corpus.py`.

